Name: tsh

Arguments.Name: --ttl

Arguments.Name: ssh
Arguments.Description: Run shell or execute a command on a remote SSH node
Forces ssh to try protocol version 1 only
Forces ssh to try protocol version 2 only
Forces ssh to use IPv4 addresses only
Forces ssh to use IPv6 addresses only

Arguments.Name: A
Arguments.Description: Enables forwarding of the authentication agent connection

Arguments.Name: a
Arguments.Description: Disables forwarding of the authentication agent connection

Arguments.Name: b
Arguments.Description: Use bind_address on the local machine as the source address of the connection

Arguments.Name: C
Arguments.Description: Requests compression of all data (including stdin, stdout, stderr, and data for forwarded X11 and TCP connections)

Arguments.Name: c
Arguments.Description: Selects the cipher specification for encrypting the session

Arguments.Name: D
Arguments.Description: Specifies a local 'dynamic' application-level port forwarding

Arguments.Name: e
Arguments.Description: Sets the escape character for sessions with a pty (default: '~')

Arguments.Name: F
Arguments.Description: Specifies an alternative per-user configuration file

Arguments.Name: f
Arguments.Description: Requests ssh to go to background just before command execution

Arguments.Name: g
Arguments.Description: Allows remote hosts to connect to local forwarded ports

Arguments.Name: I
Arguments.Description: Specify the PKCS#11 shared library ssh should use to communicate with a PKCS#11 token providing the user's private RSA key

Arguments.Name: i
Arguments.Description: Selects a file from which the identity (private key) for public key authentication is read

Arguments.Name: K
Arguments.Description: Enables GSSAPI-based authentication and forwarding (delegation) of GSSAPI credentials to the server

Arguments.Name: k
Arguments.Description: Disables forwarding (delegation) of GSSAPI credentials to the server

Arguments.Name: L
Arguments.Description: Specifies that the given port on the local (client) host is to be forwarded to the given host and port on the remote side

Arguments.Name: l
Arguments.Description: Specifies the user to log in as on the remote machine

Arguments.Name: M
Arguments.Description: Places the ssh client into ``master'' mode for connection sharing

Arguments.Name: m
Arguments.Description: Additionally, for protocol version 2 a comma-separated list of MAC (message authentication code) algorithms can be specified in order of preference

Arguments.Name: N
Arguments.Description: Do not execute a remote command

Arguments.Name: n
Arguments.Description: Redirects stdin from /dev/null (actually, prevents reading from stdin)

Arguments.Name: O
Arguments.Description: Control an active connection multiplexing master process

Arguments.Name: o
Arguments.Description: Can be used to give options in the format used in the configuration file

Arguments.Name: p
Arguments.Description: Port to connect to on the remote host

Arguments.Name: q
Arguments.Description: Quiet mode.  Causes most warning and diagnostic messages to be suppressed

Arguments.Name: R
Arguments.Description: Specifies that the given port on the remote (server) host is to be forwarded to the given host and port on the local side

Arguments.Name: S
Arguments.Description: Specifies the location of a control socket for connection sharing, or the string 'none' to disable connection sharing

Arguments.Name: s
Arguments.Description: May be used to request invocation of a subsystem on the remote system

Arguments.Name: V
Arguments.Description: Display the version number and exit

Arguments.Name: v
Arguments.Description: Verbose mode.  Causes ssh to print debugging messages about its progress

Arguments.Name: W
Arguments.Description: Requests that standard input and output on the client be forwarded to host on port over the secure channel

Arguments.Name: w
Arguments.Description: Requests tunnel device forwarding with the specified tun(4) devices between the client (local_tun) and the server (remote_tun)

Arguments.Name: y
Arguments.Description: Send log information using the syslog(3) system module
